{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\nOn bug close, auto-draw a best-effort `caused_by` link to the culprit ticket via git-blame, with a `--caused-by <id>` param to augment/override, plus a bug-template blame-hunt advisory. Provenance is an externally verifiable factual claim (blame is checkable), not agent self-assessment, so it is safe to derive/accept — unlike a process self-report.\n\n## Files\n- `src/rebar/metrics/blame.py` — new: single-culprit resolver.\n  - **Fixing-commit discovery:** the `<fixing-commit>` is the most recent commit in `git log` whose message resolves to THIS bug ticket — reuse `rebar._commands.verify_commit.extract_ticket_refs(message)` (verify_commit.py:55) to parse `rebar-ticket:`/subject refs and match the bug id (the same trailer-resolution the close path's `_referencing_commit_exists`, transition_close.py:32, already relies on). If no such commit exists yet (the fix may not be committed at close time), auto-derivation is skipped (returns None).\n  - **Blame target:** blame the **pre-fix** state — the parent of the fixing commit (`<fixing-commit>~1`) — over the bug's recorded `file_impact`, never post-fix HEAD (which would attribute the fixing commit itself).\n  - **\"Single-culprit\" threshold (explicit):** the resolver returns a culprit commit ONLY when a strict **majority (> 50%)** of the blamed lines across the `file_impact` files point to ONE commit AND that commit resolves to a ticket via its `rebar-ticket:` trailer; otherwise it returns None. This concretely defines \"dominant culprit\" and \"multi-commit spread ambiguity.\"\n  - Returns None (no link) on ambiguity: no `file_impact`, no fixing commit found, no >50% dominant commit, or no resolvable trailer.\n- `src/rebar/_commands/transition_close.py` — best-effort auto-link `caused_by` after the bug is closed. **CRITICAL ordering/guard:** the auto-link runs after `txn.transition_core` has committed the STATUS event, so the bug (the link SOURCE) is already `closed`; `graph._links.add_dependency` rejects links from a closed source (the `source_status == \"closed\"` raise at `_links.py:253`). The auto-link therefore writes via `graph._links._write_link_event(bug, culprit, \"caused_by\", tracker_dir)` **directly**, bypassing the closed-source and cycle guards — which add nothing for a non-blocking, non-cycle-inducing relation on a closed source. Same direct-writer path is used for the explicit `--caused-by` override applied at close time. Failure to resolve never blocks the close.\n- `src/rebar/_commands/transition.py` — parse `--caused-by <id>` and thread it end-to-end (mirrors ed13's `--class` threading, which already made `_parse_flags` return a tuple with `close_class`): `_parse_flags` returns an additional `caused_by` element (now a 5-tuple: `reason, force, force_close, close_class, caused_by`); `transition_cli` unpacks it; `transition_compute` gains a `caused_by: str = \"\"` keyword and passes it to `close_ticket`.\n- `src/rebar/_commands/transition_close.py` — `close_ticket` gains a `caused_by` parameter; on a bug close it applies the explicit `--caused-by <id>` override (and, absent that, the blame auto-derivation) via the `_write_link_event` direct-writer path described above.\n- `src/rebar/_lib_writes.py` — **CRITICAL (same gap ed13 hit):** the public library facade `transition()` (line 329) calls `transition_compute` with a fixed keyword set that does NOT include `caused_by`; add a `caused_by: str = \"\"` parameter to `transition()` and thread it into the `transition_compute` call, so library callers (not just the CLI) can set `caused_by` on close.\n- `docs/user-guide.md` — bug-template blame-hunt advisory.\n- `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_caused_by_autoderive.py` — new. **All test bug-closes MUST pass a `--class` value** (a bounded `--class` is REQUIRED on bug close after ticket ed13, which this ticket stacks on top of).\n\n## Approach\nThe culprit commit is an externally verifiable factual claim (blame is checkable), not agent self-assessment, so it is safe to derive/accept — unlike a process self-report. Reuses git blame + the existing `rebar-ticket:` trailer resolution rather than a novel mechanism. Auto-derivation is conservative: it links only on a single dominant culprit resolving to a ticket; ambiguous cases (refactors, moves, multi-commit, no `file_impact`) are left to `--caused-by` or `rebar link ... caused_by`. Best-effort — a failed resolution never blocks close, and the edge is written via `_write_link_event` directly so the closed-source guard does not silently swallow it. **Confidence semantics:** the `caused_by` LINK event itself carries NO confidence field (it is an ordinary link — `_write_link_event` writes only `{target_id, relation}`); the \"classified vs authoritative\" distinction is applied by the *consuming* provenance metric (the registry/reader), which treats a blame-auto-derived `caused_by` edge as `classified`-confidence evidence, never as an authoritative structural fact. This ticket does not add a confidence field to the link; it only draws the edge.\n\n## Tests\n- Integration (real temp git repo + store): a bug whose fix edits lines last changed (pre-fix) by a single commit carrying a `rebar-ticket:` trailer auto-gets a `caused_by` link to that ticket (closing with `--class`); an ambiguous multi-commit blame draws no auto-link; `--caused-by <id>` always sets the link.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_caused_by_autoderive.py` passes: closing a bug (`--class regression`) over a single-culprit fixture yields a `caused_by` link to the resolved ticket (`rebar show <bug> --output json | jq -e '.links[]|select(.relation==\"caused_by\")'`) — proving the direct-writer path defeats the closed-source guard.\n- [ ] an ambiguous two-commit blame yields no auto `caused_by` link — integration test asserts absence.\n- [ ] `rebar transition <bug> in_progress closed --class regression --caused-by <id>` sets the link regardless of blame — test asserts presence.\n- [ ] `docs/user-guide.md` gains a blame-hunt advisory section (e.g. `## Blame-Hunt Advisory`) explaining when auto-derivation applies and when to use `--caused-by` — asserted by a test/grep that the section and the `--caused-by` guidance are present."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784444425964373001,"uuid":"910c5980-b9c1-43bb-8f41-a41df5b36b3b"}